in tandem to ferry the soldiers from remote venues while Qadar and Deltadawn prayed for the battle clad, imbuing them with a chance of favor from Higher powers. Skarsh, with the help Rotgut began their Shamanistic Rituals of infusing the powers of Nature's Spirit into the mighty warriors. Seraiah the Magi had summoned her arcane companion of Earth, while Mdar the Dead was calling upon his friend of a more... departed nature.<br><br>Norkk the Mighty was requested to perform a warrior's highest honor; lead this cadre into battle. Graciously accepting this honor, the battle was nearly afoot. Turcu the Outrider volunteered for the honor of serving in place of Norkk should have he become too disabled to fight anymore. Thorgrin the Paladin sat sharpening his sword, cursing the poor elven workmanship while the others prepared for this fight of epic proportions.<br><br>Everything was set. With morale and hopes high, the final preparations were made. Ulna the Forehead used his mastery of illusionment to transform Norkk into a death-dealing whirlwind of steel. Eschaer crept carefully over to Yendar Starpyre, keeping an eye open for any unwelcome spectators.<br><br>Yendar was an old eccentric gnome, and was particularly skilled in the art of linguistics and translation. Eschaer had been asked to have Yendar translate some old Tattered Parchment by the Chief Guild master of Ebon Mask, Stanos Herkanor, some time ago. Eschaer had traveled to the Mountains of Steamfont previous to this excursion only to find that the hand-written note was beyond the expertise of the crazy gnome. However, Yendar did recognize the text well enough to identify it as a language of pure hated. Yendar also knew of an old book kept at the bedside of the Maestro of Rancor in the Plane of Hate. With this book and old records to reference, the gnome believed that he could in fact translate the old Tattered Parchment. Eschaer, not wanting to fail the Lead Guild master for rogues worldwide, traveled to the Plane of Hate, and managed to &quot;borrow&quot; the old book without the consent of the Maestro.<br><br>With the Book of Souls in hand, Yendar cross-referenced the names in the book, and was indeed able to translate the parchment. No sooner than had he finished scripting the translation, Renux Herkanor seemingly appeared from the shadows, as wry smile twitched from the corners of her lips. Before a moment had passed, the translated parchment had disappeared from Yendar's little hands and was being quickly inserted into Renux's satchel. Stanos had warned Eschaer of this moment. Renux, the traitorous daughter of Stanos, had pledged her allegiance to the sworn enemy of her father, General V'Ghera. The information on this translated parchment could be enough to throw her mighty general from his seat of power. Prior to their falling out, Stanos, a Grandmaster Rogue at the time, had trained Renux for years in the art of thievery and deception. He had told Eschaer that she would likely try to acquire the note by any means necessary. His words couldn't have rung more true as she was making her escape with Eschaer's parchment!<br><br>Looking over her shoulder to see who was in pursuit of her escape, running at top speed, slammed into a tree... or so she thought. Slightly dazed from the impact, she looked up to see that it was not a tree, but a huge ogre standing over her, smiling, blades drawn.<br><br>&quot;Gimmah dur papur now, an' we mah let ya wulk awah wiff yuh life,&quot; boomed Norkk.<br><br>Renux didn't like the way this was turning out. She had seen the cadre force in her reconnaissance, but was certain that she would have her way with this inadequately trained band of adventurers, yet here she was, lying on the ground with 50 stone of angry ogre standing over her. Renux would have to think quickly. Throwing Norkk a tired defeated look, she said &quot;Alas, I am outnumbered, and out skilled. I surrender. I shall return the parchment to you.&quot; She reached slowly into her thief’s satchel where she had hastily placed the parchment only moments before, but instead of producing the note, she produced a tiny dagger. Within a moment, she had thrown it with perfect accuracy into Norkk's thigh. As Norkk briefly fell to a knee in pain, the lady rogue bound to her feet and drew her weapons.<br><br>Seraiah's elemental, Mdar's skeleton, and the shamans' ethereal wolves were rushing to Norkk's aid. Qadar was relentlessly calling upon his God divinely intervene in Norkk's untimely death as she started to cut him to shreds. No amount of prayer could save Norkk today. As Norkk fell, the assassin turned upon the casters. Seeing this, Eschaer charged the rogue. This would be a duel of fate. By the time Eschaer had gotten within striking range, Renux had carved through three or four of his family members. Iuminya, Aelrick and Falien lay dead at Eschaer's feet... killed for no other reason than they were there.<br><br>Eschaer's blood boiled. These crimes would not go unpunished. <br><br>Eschaer's daggers flashed, and he had her attention as his dirk easily penetrated her leather tunic, creating a ruby red diamond squarely between her shoulder blades. She riposted with equivalent precision, first striking him in the chest with her dagger, then slashing him with her magical skeen. The world spun for Eschaer, completely disabled, completely vulnerable. As he felt his life slip away with every strike, more quickly than he could have imagined<br><br>With Eschaer barely clinging to life, Turcu intervened with blazing fury. As she raised her skeen over Eschaer's battered body, an instant from striking a killing blow, Turcu's whip cracked. The leather of the whip had wrapped itself around her wrist, holding the final strike back for and second... long enough for Molusi's God to open a forgiving eye upon the Dark Elf of Tier'Dal. Eschaer would be completely healed, and Molusi had saved him. This did not appease Renux, as she immediately killed the cleric, preventing anymore intervention from his God. With the cleric dead, she turned a vengeful glance upon Turcu, for saving his dark friend in her moment of glory. It was all but over in a few moments. Again, her sword had worked its magic, this time on Turcu. Turcu would not die, however. It was Qadar this time who prayed hard enough, pulling Turcu from the bony clutches of Lady Death. Renux, seeing how well it had worked before, made it her personal mission to kill Qadar at this point, briefly forgetting about Turcu and Eschaer. Qadar had nearly lived, but fell victim to the rogue's dagger just moments before little Fawwna could save him with a healing touch. With the cleric dead, she again turned her attention to Turcu. As the outrider fought a losing battle with the rogue, Eschaer found his daggers driving at her spine again.<br><br>This time Renux would kill Eschaer, and she would stop at nothing to do it. Eschaer saw this pure hatred in her eye... and smiled, winked and blew her a kiss. Then Eschaer ran.<br><br>The Lady of the Dagger chased Eschaer. She ran after him through the valleys and plateaus of the Mountains of Steamfont. Disregarding all other attacks from the ethereal wolves, skeletons, and elementals, she ran after him. Renux would have BLOOD! This pure hatred would be the death of Renux, however. With pure intent on killing Eschaer, she gave no regard to her own well-being. Renux was dying by the hands of the summoned companions of the Magi, Necromancer and Shamans... and by the dwarven paladin Thorgrin. Then the unimaginable happened.<br><br>While crossing a ridge with Renux in pursuit, Eschaer slipped on a slick rock, falling on his side. Renux was on him in a moment, and again, the world spun for Eschaer. He would certainly die this time. His life slipped to nothingness as his world spun into oblivion. Again, the powers that be intervened. Little Fawwna had told herself that she wouldn't lose another one, dammit... not on her watch. And with that, the little druid gave Eschaer the life of nature. She was a strong little elf, but still young, and the healing powers were light... but bought enough time for Eschaer to regain his sense of direction and run again. This time Renux was in much closer pursuit however, as Eschaer was badly injured and unable to run so swiftly. The dagger pierced his back, and then again in his thigh.<br><br>&quot;She has to be nearly dead. I cannot have come this far to FAIL,&quot; thought Eschaer as he felt his life drain for a third time. A sharp, deep pain went through his other thigh, and Eschaer fell to his knees, unable to run anymore. Renux would kill him, and it was there that Eschaer would die.<br><br>With the cadre force nearly slaughtered into oblivion by a single rogue, Eschaer did something that he, an agnostic Dark Elf would have never thought to do. On his knees, with eyes closed and death on his shoulder, he prayed for the lost souls on this battlefield. It was the only thing left to do. He didn't know who he was praying to, or why he felt compelled to do it, he simply did it.<br><br>Before the first word of prayer had crossed his lips, he felt... perfect. There was no pain. Everything was clear. He looked down to see his wounds healed. He looked up to see Deltadawn on a nearby ridge. Maybe she had done it herself. Maybe just the thought of the well-being for the dead on the battlefield was enough to have her God smile upon him... he didn't know, and he didn't have time to ponder.<br><br>He had a fight to finish.<br><br>With vengeance in his eye, and sorrow for the fallen in his heart, he stood and turned to Renux.<br><br>He had been right; Renux looked dead. Her legs were raw meat from being repeatedly struck by ethereal wolves. Her arms were bruised and cut from wrist to shoulder. Her tunic tattered and blood-soaked from countless slashes and stabs. Little Thorgrin was hurt, but continuously slashing her like a man on some dam fool crusade. With renewed strength and her attention drawn to the paladin, this bought Eschaer enough time to again backstab this bitch one last time. Again, the dark rogue's daggers flashed. But it wasn't enough... To Eschaer's dismay and disbelief, she slaughtered Thorgrin before Deltadawn could save the little dwarf.<br><br>It seemed that Renux wanted to kill one Thorgrin just to spite Eschaer before surrendering herself to defeat and fleeing, for as soon as Thorgrin's body lay lifeless on that battlefield, she fled. Renux, however, was too battered to run. As she limped away from the survivors, everyone still standing joined the battle. Little Stilgore offered his steel while Deltadawn blasted the rogue wench with magic.<br><br>Renux rounded a ridge with the band of &quot;ill-adept&quot; adventurers certain to kill her with any strike now.<br><br>Turcu had fought diligently in the fight, and had been mortally wounded. Without the healing touch of Qadar, he had withdrawn himself from the battlefield when he was nearly slain. Clinging onto life and hoping to be healed, Turcu had hidden himself away from the battlefield, just beyond a ridge yonder. This was the ridge that Renux had just rounded. Seeing the one that had saved the dark rogue in the first place, she made it her dying effort to slay him. She looked upon Turcu with dead eyes, letting her dagger fall into his chest, killing him. The survivors were in utter shock. She lay dead next to Turcu a mere moment after she had killed him, Skarsh getting the finishing blow.<br><br>Eschaer knelt over the dead assassin's body... in her satchel he found what he should have never had to fight for. The translated parchment was there, and in good shape. The ink had smeared a little, as it had still been wet when she snatched it from the little gnome's hands, but the document was still legible. He leaned over to her, and whispered something in her lifeless ear and stood.<br><br>Eschaer looked over the battlefield. It was a sickening sight. The lifeless bodies of nearly his entire family lie about, the grassy mountainside a shiny tint of blood red with darker stains here and there. The smell of rust hung heavy in the damp air.<br><br>&quot;She had been trained very well to slaughter my family fifteen to one...&quot; Eschaer thought to himself. <br><br>He turned to the survivors. Little Deltadawn stood with Stilgore and Skarsh. Eschaer began to collect the corpses as Deltadawn called upon her God to grant her family another chance in life. The victory was bittersweet. It had been a dreary morning, indeed.<br><br>They marched onto the battlefield that dreary morning, steel sharp and minds keen. <br><br>They were the Twilight Raiders. <br><br>They marched onto the battlefield as One. And as One Family, they reigned VICTORIOUS!<br><br>HAIL RAIDERS!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Eschaer posted this on our guild board and I thought it was quite good so I decided to share it with you all.<br><br>-Turcu <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFF7D6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/ubaberk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Baberk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#6C8361>(4/6/02 4:57:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsroleplayforum.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=125.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Tale of Steamfont</span><hr size=1> Ineed a nice job.Ppl dont spend the time reading stuff,but its fun.It kept my interest.Nice.<br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://213.96.1.51/UberSK.htm">213.96.1.51/UberSK.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFF8Dc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/uamundzenn.showPubli